LStream & Live Streaming Module Documentation
1. Project Overview
LStream is developed to broadcast media streams to remote servers (RTMP, RTSP, etc.) using an FFmpeg-based architecture. Implementing the LSink interface, this class aims to provide low-latency broadcasting by creating an asynchronous streaming pipeline.
2. Core Components
A. LStream (Streaming Engine)
Manages the entire lifecycle of the broadcast stream.
    • Latency Prevention: Configured with tune=zerolatency and ultrafast preset settings, it operates with a "GOP" (Group of Pictures) size of 30 frames (approximately 1-2 seconds), which is optimal for live streaming.
    • Asynchronous Streaming Pipeline: Incoming frames are stored in a thread-safe manner within m_frameQueue. The m_streamThread continuously monitors this queue to send packets to the streaming server.
    • Synchronization: Audio and video are aligned using PTS (Presentation Time Stamp) values to prevent drift during the broadcast.
B. FFmpeg Integration
    • Container Management: Supports streaming protocols such as RTMP via libavformat.
    • Image Processing: Uses libswscale to convert source images to the broadcast format (resolution, color space).
    • Audio Processing: Uses libswresample to normalize the audio sample rate and channel count to the target broadcast format (e.g., 48kHz Stereo).
3. Core Workflows
Broadcast Initialization
    • The destination is defined using setStreamUrl and setStreamKey.
    • initFFmpeg() is called to create the streaming container and codec context configurations.
    • The streamLoop() thread is started to begin processing the data in m_frameQueue.
Frame Processing (Frame Pipeline)
    • Source objects connect to LStream as a sink.
    • Incoming frames are cloned using av_frame_clone and added to the queue.
    • Packets encoded in H.264 or AAC format using libavcodec are transmitted to the remote server via av_interleaved_write_frame.
4. Usage Example
The following example demonstrates how to configure an LStream object and start a broadcast:
C++
#include "LStream.h"
#include <iostream>

void runStreamingExample() {
    LStream streamer;

    // 1. Setting Broadcast Information
    streamer.setStreamUrl("rtmp://live.twitch.tv/app/");
    streamer.setStreamKey("live_XXXX_XXXX");

    // 2. Video and Audio Settings
    streamer.setVideoCodec("libx264");
    streamer.setVideoBitrate(4000); // 4 Mbps
    streamer.setAudioCodec("aac");
    streamer.setAudioBitrate(128);

    // 3. Format Configuration
    videoFormatProps vProps;
    vProps.width = 1920;
    vProps.height = 1080;
    vProps.fps = 30.0;
    streamer.setVideoFormat(vProps);

    // 4. Starting the Broadcast
    std::cout << "Starting stream..." << std::endl;
    if (streamer.Start()) {
        std::cout << "Stream started successfully!" << std::endl;
        
        // After this point, you send frames from LObject 
        // using streamer.pushVideoFrame(frame)
        
        // To stop the stream:
        // streamer.Stop();
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Failed to start stream!" << std::endl;
    }
}
Technical Tips:
    • Optimizing Latency: If you experience latency during streaming, ensure that the {"preset", "ultrafast"} setting is active in m_customOptions.
    • Queue Management: To protect system resources, the frame-dropping logic inside pushVideoFrame runs automatically when m_frameQueue is full.
5. Streaming Statistics (Stats)
You can use the LStream::getStats method to monitor network conditions, frame drops, and latency in real-time.
Stats Structure
C++
struct Stats {
    int64_t bytesSent = 0;       // Total data sent (bytes)
    double durationSec = 0.0;    // Total broadcast duration
    double fps = 0.0;           // Instantaneous broadcast frame rate
    int droppedFrames = 0;      // Frame loss in the streaming pipeline
    int bufferedFrames = 0;     // Frames waiting to be processed
    double avSyncMs = 0.0;       // Audio-video synchronization drift
};
Example Statistics Usage
While the stream is running, you can retrieve this data using a QTimer or a loop and reflect it in your UI:
C++
#include "LStream.h"
#include <iostream>

void displayStreamingStats(LStream& streamer) {
    LStream::Stats stats;
    streamer.getStats(stats);

    std::cout << "--- Streaming Statistics ---" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Data Sent: " << stats.bytesSent / 1024 << " KB" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Frame Rate (FPS): " << stats.fps << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Dropped Frames: " << stats.droppedFrames << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Buffered Frames: " << stats.bufferedFrames << std::endl;
    
    if (stats.avSyncMs > 100.0) {
        std::cout << "WARNING: High sync drift!" << std::endl;
    }
}
Important Notes:
    • Queue Management: If the bufferedFrames value is constantly increasing, it means your internet upload speed is insufficient to support the chosen videoBitrate. It is recommended to select a lower bit rate.
    • Synchronization: The avSyncMs value measures whether audio and video are at the same timestamp (PTS). A value close to 0 indicates high broadcast quality. 
